    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\r\n\r\nNo\r\n\r\n### Feature description\r\n\r\n**Why?**\r\nCurrently unifying the look and feel of neovim ui is kind of hard to deal with because of absence of such options.\r\n\r\nFrom user perspective if you want something more unique then `single` or `rounded` borders you would need for every plugin that is using floating windows at some point to add few lines of code for controlling (if plugin allows this) its look.\r\n\r\nFrom plugin author perspective you need to make it public such an option (complicate plugin config) instead of something like `nvim_open_win(.... { border = vim.get_float_border() }` and forget about it.\r\n\r\n---\r\nBecause of `:h api-contract` and some limitation of vim options (can't be real lists or dicts) it's hard to deal with such problem.\r\n\r\n<details><summary><b>What I suggest</b></summary>\r\nNot sure if it is the best thing (maybe community/devs can find a better one solution).\r\nLets introduce two new options and one new function (`vim` or `vim.api`):\r\n- first option is `floatborder` (or you name it) which can be one of already provided options of the border for `nvim_open_win` such as *none, single, double, rounded, solid, shadow* or any others plus one new option named *borderchars*.\r\n- second option is `borderchars` itself with is a comma-separated characters (or maybe something like *fillchars* for more conrol) for the border the same as array for `nvim_open_win()` border option.\r\n- our new function should just from `floatborder` and `borderchars` options generate string or array required for `nvim_open_win()` border option.\r\n\r\nSo at the end users will just need to change such two options to have the same borders. And plugin authors just to call the function to generate border option when they add `nvim_open_win()` in their plugin.\r\n</details>\r\n\r\nAny ideas how to improve this suggestion? What do you think overall about this feature request?\r\n\r\n---\r\n**EDIT** as **bfredl** suggested just some lua option like `vim.ui.border_style` seems even less work to implement this and for users and plugin authors to use.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
